URL:https://japanesegarden.org/events/enduring-impressions-contemporary-woodblock-prints/
SUMMARY:Enduring Impressions: Contemporary Woodblock Prints
DESCRIPTION:\n\n\n\n\nThis March\, step into a world where nature-themed prints meet Portland Japanese Garden’s springtime vibrance in Enduring Impressions: Contemporary Woodblock Prints. Featuring the art of mokuhanga (木版画)\, Japanese-style woodblock printmaking\, this exhibition reveals how a centuries-old tradition is experiencing a contemporary revival as artists around the world use the quiet power and unique characteristics of woodblock printmaking to create captivating works of art. \n\n\n\nMokuhanga&nbsp\;has been&nbsp\;embraced&nbsp\;as an&nbsp\;environmentally friendly&nbsp\;art&nbsp\;form&nbsp\;that uses wood\, water-based pigments\,&nbsp\;and paper&nbsp\;made&nbsp\;from plant&nbsp\;fibers.&nbsp\;The&nbsp\;exhibition’s&nbsp\;featured artists are among&nbsp\;the&nbsp\;growing&nbsp\;international&nbsp\;movement&nbsp\;where&nbsp\;meticulously crafted&nbsp\;art prints&nbsp\;incorporating&nbsp\;these&nbsp\;traditional tools and techniques&nbsp\;are complemented by&nbsp\;alternative&nbsp\;printmaking&nbsp\;technologies&nbsp\;and strategies for&nbsp\;contemporary&nbsp\;expression.&nbsp\;This exhibition&nbsp\;marks the Garden’s first collaboration&nbsp\;with&nbsp\;the&nbsp\;Honolulu Museum of Art and&nbsp\;is&nbsp\;co-curated by Stephen Salel\, the Museum’s Curator of Japanese Art.&nbsp\;Across the&nbsp\;galleries&nbsp\;at Portland Japanese Garden\,&nbsp\;Enduring Impressions&nbsp\;presents&nbsp\;an eclectic&nbsp\;range of contemporary&nbsp\;prints\,&nbsp\;&nbsp\;alongside&nbsp\;a behind-the-scenes look at the process\,&nbsp\;history&nbsp\;and future&nbsp\;of this iconic art&nbsp\;form.&nbsp\;&nbsp\;\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nThe Pavilion Gallery\n\n\n\nThe Pavilion Gallery&nbsp\;features the original six&nbsp\;artists who&nbsp\;participated&nbsp\;in the Honolulu Museum of Art’s iteration of the exhibition in fall of 2025:&nbsp\;&nbsp\;\n\n\n\n\nYoonmi&nbsp\;Nam\,&nbsp\;Korean&nbsp\;artist and&nbsp\;professor of printmaking at the University of Kansas&nbsp\;&nbsp\;\n\n\n\n\n\nApril Vollmer\, New York-based printmaker and author of Japanese Woodblock Print Workshop: A Modern Guide to the Ancient Art of&nbsp\;Mokuhanga (2015)&nbsp\;&nbsp\;\n\n\n\n\n\nKenji&nbsp\;Takenaka\, Kyoto-based&nbsp\;printmaker&nbsp\;and&nbsp\;leader of the&nbsp\;Takezasadō&nbsp\;Printmaking Workshop&nbsp\;&nbsp\;\n\n\n\n\n\nHiroki\, Setsuko\,&nbsp\;and&nbsp\;Miho&nbsp\;Morinoue\,&nbsp\;Hawai’i-based&nbsp\;family of artists\, running the community-focused&nbsp\;Donkey Mill Art Center&nbsp\;in&nbsp\;Hōlualoa\,&nbsp\;Hawai‘i &nbsp\;&nbsp\;\n\n\n\n\nAccompanying the original six artists is&nbsp\;work by&nbsp\;Portland-based&nbsp\;illustrator and printmaker\,&nbsp\;Aya Morton\,&nbsp\;whose&nbsp\;mokuhanga-inspired prints merge silkscreen with relief printing&nbsp\;processes&nbsp\;to produce&nbsp\;beautifully rendered scenes of&nbsp\;the&nbsp\;Pacific Northwest.\n\n\n\nThe Calvin and&nbsp\;Mayho&nbsp\;Tanabe Gallery\n\n\n\nThroughout history\, the process behind the art of&nbsp\;mokuhanga&nbsp\;has&nbsp\;inspired artists across cultures and eras.&nbsp\;Complementing the contemporary woodblock prints highlighted in the Pavilion Gallery\,&nbsp\;take a&nbsp\;glimpse at the diverse&nbsp\;accomplishments&nbsp\;of this printmaking tradition through the&nbsp\;remarkable&nbsp\;work&nbsp\;of two pivotal artists: Kawase&nbsp\;Hasui&nbsp\;(1883-1957)\, one of Japan’s most iconic artists of the 20th&nbsp\;century\, and Portland-born&nbsp\;Richard Diebenkorn (1922–1993)\, a prominent American&nbsp\;Abstract&nbsp\;Expressionist. Though visually distinct\, their prints are nonetheless linked across time and space by the meticulous craftsmanship and expert-driven processes at the heart of traditional&nbsp\;mokuhanga.&nbsp\;&nbsp\;\n\n\n\nThe Tanabe Gallery&nbsp\;exhibition&nbsp\;was&nbsp\;made possible&nbsp\;through support from:&nbsp\;The&nbsp\;Lavenberg&nbsp\;Collection of Japanese Prints&nbsp\;The&nbsp\;Collections of Jordan D. Schnitzer and His Family Foundation&nbsp\;\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nMajor support provided by:\n\n\n\n\n\nWith support from The Robert F. Lange Foundation\n
CATEGORIES:Art Exhibitions
LOCATION:Pavilion Gallery & Tanabe Gallery\, 611 SW Kingston Ave.\, Portland\, OR\, 97205\, United States
GEO:45.51862;-122.70843109999998
