DTSTART:20261017T170000Z
DTEND:20261019T003000Z
DTSTAMP:20260129T200436Z
URL:https://japanesegarden.org/events/impressions-of-autumn-ikebana-exhibition/
SUMMARY:Impressions of Autumn Ikebana Exhibition
DESCRIPTION:\nA Heika Upright Style with millet\, chrysanthemums and peony leaves by Carolyn Alter. \n\n\n\nPresented by&nbsp\;the&nbsp\;Ohara School of Ikebana Oregon Chapter&nbsp\;\n\n\n\nSaturday\, October 17th\, 2026&nbsp\;/ 10:00am – 5:30pm*&nbsp\;Sunday\, October 18th\, 2026&nbsp\;/ 10:00am –&nbsp\;5:00pm*&nbsp\;\n\n\n\n*This show will also be open during Member Hours starting at 9:00am&nbsp\;\n\n\n\nThe stunning displays of brilliant reds and golds in autumn and ikebana arrangements have two things in common\, they are both fleeting. Visit Portland Japanese Garden during our special two-day horticultural exhibition\, Impressions of Autumn\, presented by Ohara School of Ikebana\, Oregon Chapter. Over this October weekend\, you’ll be able to appreciate the beauty of both fall in the Garden and ikebana arrangements in the Yanai Classroom in the Jordan Schnitzer Japanese Learning Arts Center. \n\n\n\nIkebana\, the Japanese art of flower arranging\, has been translated as “living flowers” or “giving life to flowers\,” and is unique from other approaches to flower arrangement.&nbsp\;&nbsp\;\n\n\n\nArtists from&nbsp\;the&nbsp\;Ohara School of Ikebana Oregon Chapter&nbsp\;look forward to embracing the season and&nbsp\;showcasing&nbsp\;artistry that will complement&nbsp\;the&nbsp\;Garden’s atmosphere.&nbsp\;Carolyn Alter\, Head Teacher of the Ohara School of Ikebana Oregon Chapter\,&nbsp\;states&nbsp\;the artists&nbsp\;seek&nbsp\;to “bring the essence of nature into their arrangements.”&nbsp\;&nbsp\;\n\n\n\nAbout&nbsp\;the Ohara School of Ikebana&nbsp\;\n\n\n\nThe Ohara School of Ikebana emphasizes connecting with nature season by season\,&nbsp\;utilizing&nbsp\;the materials individual character\, and arranging it in a naturalistic way. They are known for&nbsp\;moribana\, which broke with the more traditional and formal vertical styles\, creating new horizontal “landscape” arrangements\, with flowers “heaped” (moru) in lower plate-like containers.&nbsp\;&nbsp\;&nbsp\;\n\n\n\nAbout Carolyn Alter&nbsp\;\n\n\n\nCarolyn Alter with the Ohara School of Ikebana at Portland Japanese Garden\n\n\n\nCarolyn Alter began studying&nbsp\;in&nbsp\;the Ohara School of Ikebana under Sensei Kitty (Natsue) Akre in 1993. She began teaching weekly classes and founded Wednesday’s Flowers in 2012. She is a long-time member of Portland Japanese Garden\, Ikebana International and the North American Ohara Teachers Association. She has attended&nbsp\;numerous&nbsp\;ikebana conferences in the US and taken classes in Japan\, chaired many exhibitions\, given&nbsp\;numerous&nbsp\;demonstrations\, and is certified as an Associate First Term Master of the Ohara School of Ikebana. She is also the Head Teacher and Treasurer of the Oregon Chapter of the Ohara School. As a physical therapist for more than thirty years\, she appreciates the healing aspects of nature through practicing ikebana. She loves being outdoors\, gardening\, and the beauty of Japanese culture.&nbsp\;\n\n\n
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://wpmedia.japanesegarden.org/w:1575/h:1442/q:mauto/process:47174/id:dc97621f7e13a96d4e136b071e3131d9/https://japanesegarden.org/CarolynAlter_arrangement_H.jpg
CATEGORIES:Botanical Exhibitions
LOCATION:Yanai Classroom\, 611 SW Kingston Ave.\, Portland\, Oregon\, 97205\, United States
GEO:45.51862;-122.70843109999998
