BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:5097@japanesegarden.org
DTSTART:20261121T211500Z
DTEND:20261122T001500Z
DTSTAMP:20260113T194422Z
URL:https://japanesegarden.org/events/miniature-ikebana-workshop-with-nana-goto-bellerud-sogetsu-school/
SUMMARY:Miniature Ikebana Workshop with Nana Goto Bellerud\, Sogetsu School
DESCRIPTION:\nMiniature ikebana arrangements by Nana Bellerud.\n\n\n\nVisit Portland Japanese Garden to learn a&nbsp\;method of&nbsp\;ikebana&nbsp\;that takes the beauty of this Japanese artform&nbsp\;and puts it into a tiny form!&nbsp\;Nana&nbsp\;Goto&nbsp\;Bellerud\, Branch Director of Sogetsu Portland\,&nbsp\;will teach a basic introduction to ikebana\, a Japanese and unique approach to flower arrangement that translates to “living flowers” or “giving life to flowers.”&nbsp\;She&nbsp\;will be&nbsp\;focusing on miniature arrangements.&nbsp\;No&nbsp\;previous&nbsp\;experience is needed.&nbsp\;\n\n\n\nThe Sogetsu School of Ikebana believes ikebana can be practiced anytime\, anywhere\, by anyone. The three main elements designers use are line\,&nbsp\;color\, and&nbsp\;mass\, with an emphasis on the designer’s individual artistic expression and creativity.&nbsp\;Miniature ikebana adds an&nbsp\;additional&nbsp\;layer of nuance.&nbsp\;\n\n\n\nAn assortment of miniature containers for ikebana.\n\n\n\n“When making the miniature ikebana of Sogetsu\,&nbsp\;we&nbsp\;first look for small\, used&nbsp\;items such as shot glasses or seashells\,”&nbsp\;Bellerud&nbsp\;shares. “Original&nbsp\;vessels&nbsp\;can be made of soft&nbsp\;metals&nbsp\;or clay.&nbsp\;After the&nbsp\;container has been chosen\, we consider the plant materials. We&nbsp\;carefully&nbsp\;observe&nbsp\;the&nbsp\;different parts–petals\, pistils\,&nbsp\;stamens\, fruits\, leaves\, branches\, and stems—to make new discoveries of their distinctive appearance.  Then&nbsp\;we&nbsp\;combine the containers with plant parts to create&nbsp\;a&nbsp\;unique micro-world.”&nbsp\;\n\n\n\nParticipants will first&nbsp\;attend a public&nbsp\;ikebana&nbsp\;demonstration&nbsp\;at 1:15pm&nbsp\;in the Cathy Rudd Cultural Corner&nbsp\;alongside visitors to the Garden. The demonstration will cover&nbsp\;the basic concepts\, techniques\,&nbsp\;and&nbsp\;tools&nbsp\;of&nbsp\;ikebana.&nbsp\;&nbsp\;\n\n\n\nFollowing the demonstration\, workshop participants&nbsp\;will be&nbsp\;taken into their exclusive workshop in the Yanai Family Classroom.&nbsp\;Beyond simply producing a beautiful work of art with flowers and natural objects\,&nbsp\;Bellerud&nbsp\;will show you how&nbsp\;ikebana&nbsp\;explores artistic concepts such as balance\, contrast\, and negative space.&nbsp\;During the workshop\, participants&nbsp\;will create three basic miniature arrangements in&nbsp\;very small&nbsp\;vessels\, which will be provided by the instructor.&nbsp\;&nbsp\;\n\n\n\nREGISTRATION&nbsp\;INFO&nbsp\;\n\n\n\nPrice&nbsp\;\n\n\n\nMembers: $65&nbsp\;\n\n\n\nPublic: $80&nbsp\;\n\n\n\nSpace is limited to 18&nbsp\;participants.&nbsp\;All tools will be provided. The workshop fee includes a set of three unique mini vases and the plant materials used in the workshop\, which participants will take home after the workshop.&nbsp\;Registration fees are non-refundable.&nbsp\;&nbsp\;\n\n\n\nAbout Nana Goto&nbsp\;Bellerud&nbsp\;\n\n\n\nPhoto courtesy of Nana Bellerud\n\n\n\nNana Goto&nbsp\;Bellerud&nbsp\;has been&nbsp\;studying&nbsp\;the Sogetsu School of ikebana since 2005 and continues to be inspired and have new insights from its teachings.  Bellerud&nbsp\;demonstrates\,&nbsp\;exhibits\, and teaches ikebana at a wide range of venues including the Portland Art Museum\, Portland&nbsp\;Japanese Garden\,&nbsp\;Gresham Japanese Garden\, various garden clubs\, and schools.&nbsp\;Through her demonstrations and workshops\, she&nbsp\;seeks&nbsp\;to introduce others to the art of ikebana and to intrigue and inspire them. Beyond simply producing a beautiful work of art with flowers and natural objects\, she shows her audience how ikebana explores artistic concepts such as balance\, contrast\, and negative space. Bellerud&nbsp\;has been creating and posting daily ikebana on Instagram (@nana_bellerud) and actively teaching via live interactive video.&nbsp\;\n\n\n\nBellerud&nbsp\;holds Master of Arts degrees in Political Science and Agribusiness Management from Mississippi State University and has taught Japanese Culture at Mt. Hood Community College. &nbsp\;She&nbsp\;is currently serving as President of Ikebana International Portland Chapter #47 and Branch Director of Sogetsu Portland. &nbsp\;Bellerud&nbsp\;is also a member of the Ikebana Iwaya Fund Board of Directors.  &nbsp\;\n\n\n\nAbout the Sogestu Shcool of Ikebana\n\n\n\nThe Sogetsu School is known for its willingness to explore&nbsp\;new ideas&nbsp\;and materials. The founder\,&nbsp\;Sofu&nbsp\;Teshigahara\, broke away from tradition in 1927 to&nbsp\;establish&nbsp\;his new school based on the belief that anyone can create ikebana anywhere\, and with&nbsp\;almost anything. The Sogetsu philosophy advocates that ikebana should be part of a lifestyle\, appreciated by many people from all over the world\, rather than being considered an exclusive aspect of Japanese culture to be enjoyed by a limited number of people.&nbsp\;\n\n\n\nPast Participants Appreciated\n\n\n\nI learned something new\, found a potential new hobby\, and got to&nbsp\;encounter&nbsp\;a new way of thinking I can apply to multiple avenues in my life.&nbsp\;&nbsp\;\n\n\n\nHaving fun being creative with beautiful pottery and beautiful natural elements.&nbsp\;&nbsp\;\n\n\n\nThe instructor was so&nbsp\;down-to-earth&nbsp\;and funny!&nbsp\;\n\n\n\nThe vibrancy of the instructor\, the artfulness of the containers\, the tools and supplies felt&nbsp\;substantial&nbsp\;and attainable.&nbsp\;&nbsp\;\n\n\n\nHands on\, creative\, and of course the instructor was welcoming\,&nbsp\;kind&nbsp\;and supportive.&nbsp\;&nbsp\;\n\n\n
